Modern HMR systems (Vite, esbuild) standardise on the `import.meta.hot` runtime API. A module that wants to participate writes:

```js
if (import.meta.hot) {
  import.meta.hot.accept((newModule) => {
    // run cleanup, install newModule's exports
  });
  import.meta.hot.dispose((data) => {
    // hand state forward to the next instance
  });
}
```

The dev server tracks which modules have an `accept` handler and only pushes updates that can be absorbed without a full reload. If a changed module has no `accept`, the update propagates upward to the importer; if no module along the chain accepts, the page reloads.

Webpack's older HMR API uses `module.hot.accept` with similar semantics. The convergence on `import.meta.hot` (an ESM-native form) is part of Vite's appeal: it works without webpack-specific wrappers and integrates cleanly with native ESM dev servers.
